    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-07T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-07T14:00:00-05:00" n="121"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./77: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-07T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 7, 1934—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>149. Your 173, July 7th. Contrary to <persName>Litvinoff</persName>’s statement
                    to you, <persName corresp="#p_TAA1">Troyanovsky</persName> has not made the
                    inquiry alleged and on the other hand has indicated his hope that he would be
                    instructed to take up debt negotiations here.</p>
                <pb facs="0221" n="115" xml:id="pg_115"/>
                <p>At a recent meeting of the Export-Import Bank there was much talk of the futility
                    of maintaining the bank, which involves expense, if the Soviet has no intention
                    of making a real effort to effect an agreement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
